392. Langen (Plancin. Studien, p. 274) would reject this line on the ground that semper secie is absum, coming from a prisoner cap- tured only the day before (cf. 110 ff), and that such expressions as are here found would not be used by a slave.

394. nam quidem: is commonly changed to nam equidem, on the ground that in the eight other passages where the phrase occurs it takes the latter form. In Ps. 260, however, C. has quidem, and all the Mss. have quidem in the present passage. There seems no suffi- cient ground for changing this reading.

403. me aduersatum tibi: Ι see no sufficient reason for changing this reading of the Mss. It is in perfect harmony with (nos) incer nos fuisse ingenio haud discordabili in 402. Tyndarus is dwelling upon the mutual relations of good-will existing between them, and neque me aduersatum tibi is needed to carry out this idea after the preceding neque te commeruisse culpam.
